{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775852254757,"sessionID":"ses_286f6aed7ffekYy405f9z7HzpW","part":{"id":"prt_d790af5fd0018MMGAO0LQ0Y6KU","messageID":"msg_d7909fcc20010vktCFKLckYxyI","sessionID":"ses_286f6aed7ffekYy405f9z7HzpW","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-eb97a8b624a7428e8efd3e3bdccca6cd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/changes/AR-011/proposal.md","content":"# AR-011 — Router JWT 认证与签发 Proposal\n\n## Purpose\n\nImplement JWT authentication and signing capabilities for the AgentCube Router module. This provides secure service-to-service communication and identity verification between Router and sandbox pods. The JWT component:\n\n1. **Token Generation**: Creates signed JWT tokens with RS256 algorithm containing session/sandbox identity claims\n2. **Key Management**: Generates RSA key pairs (2048-bit) for signing and verification\n3. **Token Claims**: Embeds session_id, sandbox_id, namespace, name as standard claims with 5-minute expiration\n4. **Issuer Identity**: Sets `agentcube-router` as standard issuer for service identification\n5. **Key Persistence**: Supports PEM encoding/decoding for Kubernetes Secret storage\n6. **Public Key Distribution**: Provides GetPublicKey for downstream verification\n\n## Scope\n\n### In Scope\n\n| Deliverable | Description |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| `pkg/router/jwt.go` | JWTManager implementation with GenerateToken, key management, PEM encoding |\n| `pkg/router/jwt_test.go` | Unit tests for token generation, parsing, expiration, key encoding |\n| `pkg/router/errors.go` | JWTSigningError type with APIStatus implementation |\n| `pkg/router/doc.go` | JWTManagerInterface definition |\n| RSA Key Generation | 2048-bit RSA keys for RS256 signing |\n| Token Expiration | 5-minute default expiration (jwtExpiration constant) |\n| PEM Encoding | encodePrivateKeyPEM, encodePublicKeyPEM, loadPrivateKeyPEM helpers |\n| Kubernetes Secret Support | IdentitySecretName, PrivateKeyDataKey, PublicKeyDataKey constants |\n\n### Key Components\n\n```\npkg/router/\n├── JWTManager (jwt.go)\n│   ├── privateKey: *rsa.PrivateKey (2048-bit)\n│   ├── publicKey: *rsa.PublicKey\n│   ├── GenerateToken(claims): RS256 signed JWT with exp, iat, iss + custom claims\n│   ├── GetPublicKey(): Returns public key for verification\n│   └── TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret(ctx): Placeholder for K8s Secret persistence\n│\n├── Constants (jwt.go)\n│   ├── rsaKeySize = 2048\n│   ├── jwtExpiration = 5 * time.Minute\n│   ├── IdentitySecretName = \"picod-router-identity\"\n│   ├── PrivateKeyDataKey = \"private.pem\"\n│   ├── PublicKeyDataKey = \"public.pem\"\n│   └── IdentityNamespace = \"default\" (or AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE env)\n│\n├── PEM Helpers (jwt.go)\n│   ├── encodePrivateKeyPEM(key): PKCS1 PEM format\n│   ├── encodePublicKeyPEM(key): PKIX PEM format\n│   └── loadPrivateKeyPEM(data): Parse PKCS1 PEM to rsa.PrivateKey\n│\n└── JWTSigningError (errors.go)\n│   ├── Err: wrapped error\n│   ├── Status() = 500\n│   ├── Code() = \"JWT_SIGNING_FAILED\"\n│   └── Message() = \"jwt signing failed\"\n```\n\n### Out of Scope\n\n- Token validation middleware (not needed; Router only generates, sandboxes verify)\n- OAuth2/OIDC protocol implementation\n- Third-party identity provider integration\n- Refresh token mechanism\n- Token revocation/blacklist\n- Fine-grained RBAC permissions\n- HS256 symmetric signing (RS256 asymmetric is preferred for distributed verification)\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Upstream Dependencies\n\n| Dependency | Impact |\n|------------|--------|\n| `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` | Core JWT library for token creation and parsing |\n| `crypto/rand` | Secure random number generation for RSA keys |\n| `crypto/rsa` | RSA key generation and signing |\n| `crypto/x509`, `encoding/pem` | PEM encoding for key storage |\n| `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Logging for TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret warning |\n| `os.Getenv` | AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE for IdentityNamespace |\n\n### Downstream Consumers\n\n| Consumer | Usage |\n|----------|-------|\n| `Server.handleInvoke` | Calls jwtManager.GenerateToken with session/sandbox claims for sandbox/claim kinds |\n| `reverse_proxy.go` | JWT token added to Authorization header when proxying to sandbox |\n| Sandbox pods | Verify JWT using Router's public key (distributed via K8s Secret) |\n| `Server` struct | Stores *JWTManager for token generation |\n\n### Breaking Change Considerations\n\n- **JWT Claims Schema**: session_id, sandbox_id, namespace, name claims are consumed by sandboxes; changing requires sandbox update\n- **Issuer Name**: `agentcube-router` is expected by verification logic; changing breaks trust\n- **Expiration Duration**: 5-minute jwtExpiration affects sandbox verification window\n- **Key Size**: 2048-bit RSA is expected; smaller keys may be rejected by validators\n- **Secret Name**: `picod-router-identity` Secret must exist for public key distribution\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Alternative 1: HS256 Symmetric Signing\n\n**Approach**: Use HMAC-SHA256 with shared secret key instead of RSA.\n\n| Aspect | Evaluation |\n|--------|------------|\n| Pros | Faster signing/verification; simpler key management (single secret) |\n| Cons | Secret must be shared with all verifiers; key rotation requires all services to update; less secure distribution |\n\n**Decision**: Rejected. RS256 asymmetric signing allows Router to keep private key secret while distributing public key to sandboxes. Key rotation only affects Router, not all verifiers.\n\n### Alternative 2: Longer Token Expiration\n\n**Approach**: Use 24-hour or longer token expiration to reduce token generation overhead.\n\n| Aspect | Evaluation |\n|--------|------------|\n| Pros | Fewer token generations; simpler session handling |\n| Cons | Stale tokens persist longer; sandbox may accept requests after session ended; security risk |\n\n**Decision**: Rejected. 5-minute expiration aligns with short-lived sandbox sessions. Tokens naturally expire before or around session timeout (30 minutes default), reducing stale token acceptance.\n\n### Alternative 3: JWT in Query Parameter\n\n**Approach**: Pass JWT token via URL query parameter instead of Authorization header.\n\n| Aspect | Evaluation |\n|--------|------------|\n| Pros | Simpler for HTTP clients without header support |\n| Cons | Token visible in URLs; logged in proxy/server logs; URL-encoded tokens break caching |\n\n**Decision**: Rejected. Authorization header (`Authorization: Bearer <token>`) is OAuth2/Bearer standard, keeps token out of URLs and logs.\n\n### Alternative 4: External JWT Service\n\n**Approach**: Delegate JWT generation to external identity service (e.g., Auth0, Keycloak).\n\n| Aspect | Evaluation |\n|--------|------------|\n| Pros | Centralized identity management; standard OAuth2/OIDC support |\n| Cons | External dependency; network latency for each token; cost; overkill for service-to-service auth |\n\n**Decision**: Rejected. Router-to-sandbox auth is simple service identity, not user auth. Self-contained JWT generation keeps architecture simple and avoids external dependencies.\n\n### Alternative 5: No JWT (Direct Service Account Auth)\n\n**Approach**: Use Kubernetes service account token for all authentication.\n\n| Aspect | Evaluation |\n|--------|------------|\n| Pros | K8s-native; no custom JWT code; automatic token rotation |\n| Cons | Service account tokens are long-lived (1 hour+); no sandbox-specific claims; shared across all pods with same SA |\n\n**Decision**: Rejected. Router JWT provides per-session claims (session_id, sandbox_id) for fine-grained sandbox identification. Service account tokens lack this granularity.\n\n## Risks\n\n| Risk | Mitigation |\n|------|------------|\n| Private key leakage | Keep private key in Router memory; never log; use K8s Secret for persistence (read-only for sandboxes) |\n| Token replay attacks | Short 5-minute expiration; tokens tied to specific session/sandbox |\n| Clock drift causes validation failure | JWT library handles reasonable clock skew; sandboxes use jwt.WithLeeway() |\n| Key rotation disruption | TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret supports loading existing keys; generate new only on startup |\n| Public key unavailable to sandbox | Distribute via K8s Secret `picod-router-identity`; sandboxes mount as volume |\n| RSA key generation slow | Generate once at Router startup; reuse for all tokens |\n| Missing JWT claims | GenerateToken requires claims map; validation in sandbox verifies required fields |\n\n## Implementation Notes\n\n1. **Library**: `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` (latest stable)\n2. **Algorithm**: RS256 (RSA Signature with SHA-256)\n3. **Key Size**: 2048-bit RSA (balance of security and performance)\n4. **Expiration**: 5 minutes (`jwtExpiration = 5 * time.Minute`)\n5. **Issuer**: `agentcube-router` (standard `iss` claim)\n6. **Claims**: Standard (exp, iat, iss) + Custom (session_id, sandbox_id, namespace, name)\n7. **Namespace**: `IdentityNamespace = \"default\"` or from `AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` env\n8. **Secret Name**: `picod-router-identity` for K8s Secret containing PEM-encoded keys\n9. **PEM Format**: Private key PKCS1, Public key PKIX (standard formats)\n10. **Error Handling**: JWTSigningError wraps underlying error, returns 500 status\n\n## References\n\n- [golang-jwt/jwt v5](https://github.com/golang-jwt/jwt)\n- [RFC 7519 - JSON Web Token](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7519)\n- [RFC 7518 - JSON Web Algorithms](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7518) (RS256)\n- `pkg/router/jwt.go` - Implementation\n- `pkg/router/jwt_test.go` - Test coverage\n- `pkg/router/doc.go` - JWTManagerInterface definition\n- `pkg/router/errors.go` - JWTSigningError type\n- `pkg/router/server.go:154-171` - JWT usage in handleInvoke\n- `deployment/client-go.md` - Kubernetes client reference (for Secret management)\n- `changes/AR-010/proposal.md` - Related Session Manager proposal"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/pkg/router/config.go":[],"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/pkg/router/jwt.go":[{"range":{"start":{"line":49,"character":53},"end":{"line":49,"character":64}},"severity":4,"code":"default","codeDescription":{"href":"https://pkg.go.dev/golang.org/x/tools/go/analysis/passes/modernize#any"},"source":"any","message":"interface{} can be replaced by any"},{"range":{"start":{"line":59,"character":2},"end":{"line":59,"character":16}},"severity":4,"code":"default","codeDescription":{"href":"https://pkg.go.dev/golang.org/x/tools/go/analysis/passes/modernize#mapsloop"},"source":"mapsloop","message":"Replace m[k]=v loop with maps.Copy"}],"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/pkg/router/middleware.go":[],"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/pkg/router/config_test.go":[{"range":{"start":{"line":26,"character":9},"end":{"line":26,"character":9}},"severity":3,"code":"default","codeDescription":{"href":"https://pkg.go.dev/golang.org/x/tools/go/analysis/passes/unusedwrite"},"source":"unusedwrite","message":"unused write to field TLSCert"},{"range":{"start":{"line":27,"character":8},"end":{"line":27,"character":8}},"severity":3,"code":"default","codeDescription":{"href":"https://pkg.go.dev/golang.org/x/tools/go/analysis/passes/unusedwrite"},"source":"unusedwrite","message":"unused write to field TLSKey"},{"range":{"start":{"line":29,"character":7},"end":{"line":29,"character":7}},"severity":3,"code":"default","codeDescription":{"href":"https://pkg.go.dev/golang.org/x/tools/go/analysis/passes/unusedwrite"},"source":"unusedwrite","message":"unused write to field Debug"}],"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/pkg/router/jwt_test.go":